{"title_page": "Sean Flynn (footballer)", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Sean Flynn\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|3|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England\n| height =\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = {{0|000}}?\u20131991\n| youthclubs1 = [[Halesowen Town F.C.|Halesowen Town]]\n| years1 = 1991\u20131995\n| clubs1 = [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n| caps1 = 97\n| goals1 = 9\n| years2 = 1995\u20131997\n| clubs2 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]\n| caps2 = 59\n| goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 1997\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 5\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1997\u20132000\n| clubs4 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n| caps4 = 109\n| goals4 = 7\n| years5 = 2000\u20132002\n| clubs5 = [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n| caps5 = 66\n| goals5 = 6\n| years6 = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs6 = [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]]\n| caps6 = 51\n| goals6 = 2\n| years7 = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs7 = [[Evesham United F.C.|Evesham United]]\n| years8 = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs8 = [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]\n| years9 = 2005\n| clubs9 = [[Evesham United F.C.|Evesham United]]\n| years10 = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs10 = [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]\n| years11 = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs11 = [[Bodmin Town F.C.|Bodmin Town]]\n| years12 = 2009\n| clubs12 = Mullion\n| years13 = 2009\u20132011\n| clubs13 = [[Falmouth Town A.F.C.|Falmouth Town]]\n| years14 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs14 = [[Penzance A.F.C.|Penzance]]\n| years15 = 2012\n| clubs15 = [[Falmouth Town A.F.C.|Falmouth Town]]\n| totalcaps = 387\n| totalgoals = 27\n| manageryears1 = 2009\n2018\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = Mullion\n}}\n\n'''Sean Flynn''' (born 13 March 1968) is an English former [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfielder]].\n\nFlynn notably played in the [[Premier League]] for [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], and in the [[Football League]] for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]. He finished his professional career with [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]], before moving into non-league appearing part-time for [[Evesham United F.C.|Evesham United]], [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]], [[Bodmin Town F.C.|Bodmin Town]] and [[Falmouth Town]] [[Penzance A.F.C.|Penzance]]. He was briefly player/manager of Mullion as well as holding various coaching roles at other clubs he has played for in recent years.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Coventry City===\nFlynn signed for Coventry City from non-league [[Halesowen Town F.C.|Halesowen Town]] in December 1991 and made his debut in August of the following year as a second-half substitute for David Smith in a 2\u20131 [[Premier League]] victory over [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] at [[Highfield Road]], eventually going on to record 105 games and 10 goals for the Sky Blues over the next 5 years. In August 1995, after being told by then-Coventry manager [[Ron Atkinson]], that he was no longer required at the club.\n\n===Derby County===\nFlynn dropped a division to [[Football League Championship|Division One]] to become one of [[Jim Smith (footballer)|Jim Smith]]'s first signings at [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] for a fee of \u00a3250,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Club-by-club guide: The prospects, the players to watch, the arrivals and departures|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/clubbyclub-guide-the-prospects-the-players-to-watch-the-arrivals-and-departures-1596119.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=30 April 2013|location=London|first=Ian|last=Ridley|date=13 August 1995}}</ref> Flynn's time at Derby proved to be successful as he was part of the side which finished runner-up to [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in the 1995\u201396 Division One table and earn promotion to the [[FA Premier League]] for the first time. Flynn started the Premier League campaign in the Derby first team, scoring an 80th-minute winner at [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in Derby's 5th game of the season to earn them their maiden win of a season which saw the Rams eventually finish 12th, but eventually found himself pushed to the fringes of the Derby squad, and joined [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on loan in March 1997 where he made five appearances. After 65 games and 3 goals for Derby.\n\n===Later career===\nFlynn made the switch to his boyhood club [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] for a fee of \u00a3260,000 in August 1997.\n\nAs a West Bromwich Albion fan, one of the highlights of his career was when he captained the team. He played 122 games and scored 8 goals for the Baggies. In July 2000 Flynn moved on a free transfer to Tranmere Rovers and spent 2 years there playing 82 games and scoring 11 goals in all competitions before leaving to sign for Kidderminster Harriers in August 2002 again on a free transfer and Flynn made 57 appearances scoring 2 goals before leaving in the September 2003.\n\n===Non League===\nFlynn played 436 games and scored 34 goals in his years as a pro footballer. He joined [[Evesham United F.C.|Evesham United]] in 2003, staying until 2004 when he moved to [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]. He had moved back to Evesham and then back again to Redditch by 2005 and eventually stayed with Redditch until 2008.\n\nAs well as running his business he joined [[Bodmin Town F.C.|Bodmin Town]] in 2008 where he went on to win a league and cup domestic treble, as well as player of the year, managers player of the year and supporters player of the year. In 2009, he joined Mullion as player/manager but left shortly afterward to team up with former Bodmin manager Alan Carey at [[Falmouth Town F.C.|Falmouth Town]]. Carey appointed Flynn as player/assistant manager and he remained with the club until joining [[Penzance A.F.C.|Penzance]] in 2011. He returned to Falmouth as a player in March 2012.\n\n==Career statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other{{ref label|Other|A|}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n|[[1991\u201392 in English football|1991\u201392]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|22||2||0||0||0||0||0||0||22||2\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393]]\n|[[Premier League]]\n|7||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||7||0\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 in English football|1993\u201394]]\n|Premier League\n|36||3||1||0||2||0||0||0||39||3\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 in English football|1994\u201395]]\n|Premier League\n|32||4||2||0||3||1||0||0||37||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!97!!9!!3!!0!!5!!1!!0!!0!!105!!10\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]\n|[[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|42||2||1||0||3||0||0||0||46||2\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 in English football|1996\u201397]]\n|Premier League\n|17||1||2||0||0||0||0||0||19||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!59!!3!!3!!0!!3!!0!!0!!0!!65!!3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] (loan)\n|[[1996\u201397 Stoke City F.C. season|1996\u201397]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|5||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||5||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!5!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!5!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n|[[1997\u201398 in English football|1997\u201398]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|35||2||1||0||4||0||0||0||40||2\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|38||2||1||0||2||0||0||0||41||2\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|36||4||0||0||5||1||0||0||41||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!109!!7!!2!!0!!11!!1!!0!!0!!122!!7\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n|[[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|35||1||4||0||5||0||0||0||44||1\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 in English football|2001\u201302]]\n|[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n|31||5||4||3||3||2||0||0||38||10\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!66!!6!!8!!3!!8!!2!!0!!0!!82!!11\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]]\n|[[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303]]\n|[[Football League Third Division|Third Division]]\n|45||2||1||0||1||0||3||0||50||2\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 in English football|2003\u201304]]\n|[[Football League Third Division|Third Division]]\n|6||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||7||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!51!!2!!1!!0!!2!!0!!3!!0!!57!!2\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!387!!28!!17!!3!!33!!4!!3!!0!!440!!35\n|}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n:A.&nbsp;{{note|Other}} The \"Other\" column constitutes appearances and goals in the [[Football League Trophy]].\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{Soccerbase|id=2564|name=Sean Flynn}}\n* [http://halesowentownfc.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1018&Itemid=1 Halesowen Town FC Profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flynn, Sean}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Halesowen Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Coventry City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kidderminster Harriers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Evesham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Redditch United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bodmin Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Falmouth Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Penzance A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Sean Flynn\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|3|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England\n| height =\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = {{0|000}}?\u20131991\n| youthclubs1 = [[Halesowen Town F.C.|Halesowen Town]]\n| years1 = 1991\u20131995\n| clubs1 = [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n| caps1 = 97\n| goals1 = 9\n| years2 = 1995\u20131997\n| clubs2 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]\n| caps2 = 59\n| goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 1997\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 5\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1997\u20132000\n| clubs4 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n| caps4 = 109\n| goals4 = 7\n| years5 = 2000\u20132002\n| clubs5 = [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]\n| caps5 = 66\n| goals5 = 6\n| years6 = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs6 = [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]]\n| caps6 = 51\n| goals6 = 2\n| years7 = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs7 = [[Evesham United F.C.|Evesham United]]\n| years8 = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs8 = [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]\n| years9 = 2005\n| clubs9 = [[Evesham United F.C.|Evesham United]]\n| years10 = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs10 = [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]\n| years11 = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs11 = [[Bodmin Town F.C.|Bodmin Town]]\n| years12 = 2009\n| clubs12 = Mullion\n| years13 = 2009\u20132011\n| clubs13 = [[Falmouth Town A.F.C.|Falmouth Town]]\n| years14 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs14 = [[Penzance A.F.C.|Penzance]]\n| years15 = 2012\n| clubs15 = [[Falmouth Town A.F.C.|Falmouth Town]]\n| totalcaps = 387\n| totalgoals = 27\n| manageryears1 = 2009\n2018\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = Mullion\n}}\n\n'''Sean Flynn''' (born 13 March 1968) is an English former [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfielder]].\n\nFlynn notably played in the [[Premier League]] for [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], and in the [[Football League]] for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]. He finished his professional career with [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]], before moving into non-league appearing part-time for [[Evesham United F.C.|Evesham United]], [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]], [[Bodmin Town F.C.|Bodmin Town]] and [[Falmouth Town]] [[Penzance A.F.C.|Penzance]]. He was briefly player/manager of Mullion as well as holding various coaching roles at other clubs he has played for in recent years.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Coventry City===\nFlynn signed for Coventry City from non-league [[Halesowen Town F.C.|Halesowen Town]] in December 1991 and made his debut in August of the following year as a second-half substitute for David Smith in a 2\u20131 [[Premier League]] victory over [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] at [[Highfield Road]], eventually going on to record 105 games and 10 goals for the Sky Blues over the next 5 years. In August 1995, after being told by then-Coventry manager [[Ron Atkinson]], that he was no longer required at the club.\n\n===Derby County===\nFlynn dropped a division to [[Football League Championship|Division One]] to become one of [[Jim Smith (footballer)|Jim Smith]]'s first signings at [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] for a fee of \u00a3250,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Club-by-club guide: The prospects, the players to watch, the arrivals and departures|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/clubbyclub-guide-the-prospects-the-players-to-watch-the-arrivals-and-departures-1596119.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=30 April 2013|location=London|first=Ian|last=Ridley|date=13 August 1995}}</ref> Flynn's time at Derby proved to be successful as he was part of the side which finished runner-up to [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in the 1995\u201396 Division One table and earn promotion to the [[FA Premier League]] for the first time. Flynn started the Premier League campaign in the Derby first team, scoring an 80th-minute winner at [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in Derby's 5th game of the season to earn them their maiden win of a season which saw the Rams eventually finish 12th, but eventually found himself pushed to the fringes of the Derby squad, and joined [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on loan in March 1997 where he made five appearances. After 65 games and 3 goals for Derby.\n\n===Later career===\nFlynn made the switch to his boyhood club [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] for a fee of \u00a3260,000 in August 1997.\n\nAs a West Bromwich Albion fan, one of the highlights of his career was when he captained the team. He played 122 games and scored 8 goals for the Baggies. In July 2000 Flynn moved on a free transfer to Tranmere Rovers and spent 2 years there playing 82 games and scoring 11 goals in all competitions before leaving to sign for Kidderminster Harriers in August 2002 again on a free transfer and Flynn made 57 appearances scoring 2 goals before leaving in the September 2003.\n\n===Non League===\nFlynn played 436 games and scored 34 goals in his years as a pro footballer. He joined [[Evesham United F.C.|Evesham United]] in 2003, staying until 2004 when he moved to [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]. He had moved back to Evesham and then back again to Redditch by 2005 and eventually stayed with Redditch until 2008.\n\nAs well as running his business he joined [[Bodmin Town F.C.|Bodmin Town]] in 2008 where he went on to win a league and cup domestic treble, as well as player of the year, managers player of the year and supporters player of the year. In 2009, he joined Mullion as player/manager but left shortly afterward to team up with former Bodmin manager Alan Carey at [[Falmouth Town F.C.|Falmouth Town]]. Carey appointed Flynn as player/assistant manager and he remained with the club until joining [[Penzance A.F.C.|Penzance]] in 2011. He returned to Falmouth as a player in March 2012.\n\n==Career statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other{{ref label|Other|A|}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n|[[1991\u201392 in English football|1991\u201392]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|22||2||0||0||0||0||0||0||22||2\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393]]\n|[[Premier League]]\n|7||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||7||0\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 in English football|1993\u201394]]\n|Premier League\n|36||3||1||0||2||0||0||0||39||3\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 in English football|1994\u201395]]\n|Premier League\n|32||4||2||0||3||1||0||0||37||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!97!!9!!3!!0!!5!!1!!0!!0!!105!!10\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]\n|[[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|42||2||1||0||3||0||0||0||46||2\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 in English football|1996\u201397]]\n|Premier League\n|17||1||2||0||0||0||0||0||19||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!59!!3!!3!!0!!3!!0!!0!!0!!65!!3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] (loan)\n|[[1996\u201397 Stoke City F.C. season|1996\u201397]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|5||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||5||0\n|-\n