s]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Halesowen Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Coventry City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kidderminster Harriers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Evesham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Redditch United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bodmin Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Falmouth Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Penzance A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sean_Flynn_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Chinese guardian lions", "text_new": "{{About|Chinese architectural statues|dog breeds|Lion dog (disambiguation)|uses of colloquial term foo dogs|Foo Dog (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|title='''Chinese guardian lions'''\n|pic=ImperialMaleLionGuard.jpg\n|picsize=250px\n|piccap=A [[Ming Dynasty|Ming-era]] guardian lion in the [[Forbidden City]]\n|pic2=Forbidden City Imperial Guardian Lions.jpg\n|picsize2=250px|\npiccap2=A [[Qing Dynasty|Qing-era]] guardian lion pair in the Forbidden City. Note the different appearance of the face and details in the decorative items, compared to the earlier Ming version.\n|t={{linktext|\u7345}}([[:wikt:\u7345\u5b50|\u5b50]]) |s={{linktext|\u72ee}}([[:wikt:\u72ee\u5b50|\u5b50]]) |l=[[lion]] |p=sh\u012b(zi) |w=shi(-tzu) |y= |h= |poj=\n|t2                =  {{linktext|\u77f3\u7345}}([[:wikt:\u77f3\u7345\u5b50|\u5b50]])\n|s2                = {{linktext|\u77f3\u72ee}}([[:wikt:\u77f3\u72ee\u5b50|\u5b50]])\n|l2                =  [[stone]] [[lion]]\n|p2                =  sh\u00edsh\u012b(zi)\n|w2 = shih-shih(-tzu)\n|hangul            =  {{linktext|\ud574\ud0dc}}\n|hanja             =  {{linktext|\u6d77\u6cf0}}\n|rr                =  haetae\n|kanji             =  {{linktext|\u72db\u72ac}}\n|revhep            =  [[komainu]]\n|vie=s\u01b0 t\u1eed \u0111\u00e1\n|chuhan = {{linktext|\u7345\u5b50|\ud855\udca5}}\n|lang1=Khmer\n|lang1_content= \u179f\u17b9\u1784\u17d2\u17a0<br/> singha\n|lang2=Thai\n|lang2_content= \u0e2a\u0e34\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e4c<br/> s\u0304ingh\u0304\u0312\n|lang3=Sinhalese\n|lang3_content= \u0dc3\u0dd2\u0d82\u0dc4<br/> si\u1e41ha\n|lang4=Burmese\n|lang4_content= \u1001\u103c\u1004\u103a\u1039\u101e\u1031\u1037<br/> hkyin-sae\n|lang5=Tibetan\n|lang5_content= \u0f42\u0f44\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f7a\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f7a\u0f0b<br/> gangs-seng-ge\n}}\n{{Contains Indic text}} \n'''Chinese''' or '''Imperial guardian lions''' are a traditional [[Chinese architecture|Chinese architectural]] ornament. Typically made of [[stone]], they are also known as '''stone{{nbsp}}lions''' or '''shishi'''. They are known in colloquial English as '''lion{{nbsp}}dogs''' or '''foo{{nbsp}}dogs'''. The concept, which originated and became popular in [[Chinese Buddhism]], features a pair of highly stylized [[lion]]s\u2014often one male with a ball and one female with a [[lion cub|cub]]\u2014which were thought to protect the building from harmful spiritual influences and harmful people that might be a threat. Used in [[imperial China|imperial Chinese]] palaces and [[Chinese tomb|tombs]], the lions subsequently spread to other parts of Asia including Japan (see [[komainu]]), Korea, Tibet, Thailand, Burma, Vietnam, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Cambodia, Laos, Taiwan, and Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|author=K Gorman |url=http://kgorman.ca/monster-monday-guardian-lions/ |title=Monster Monday: Guardian Lions \u2013 K. Gorman |publisher=Kgorman.ca |date= 22 January 2013|accessdate=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nStatues of guardian lions have traditionally stood in front of [[China|Chinese]] Imperial palaces, Imperial tombs, government offices, temples, and the homes of government officials and the wealthy, and were believed to have powerful [[Chinese mythology|mythic]] protective benefits. They are also used in other artistic contexts, for example on door-knockers, and in pottery. Pairs of guardian lion statues are still common decorative and symbolic elements at the entrances to restaurants, hotels, supermarkets and other structures, with one sitting on each side of the entrance, in China and in other places around the world where the Chinese people have immigrated and settled, especially in local [[Chinatown]]s.\n\nThe lions are usually depicted in pairs. When used as statuary the pair would consist of a male leaning his paw upon an embroidered ball (in imperial contexts, representing supremacy over the world) and a female restraining a playful cub that is on its back (representing nurture).<ref name=\"britannica.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/342714/Lion-of-Fo|title=Lion of Fo \u2013 Chinese art|encyclopedia=britannica.com}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nGuardian lions are referred to in various ways depending on language and context. In Chinese they are traditionally called simply ''shi'' ({{zh|c=\u7345|p=sh\u012b}}) meaning lion\u2014the word ''shi'' itself is thought to be derived from the Persian word ''\u0161er''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Xy45AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA201#v=onepage |title=Music for a Lion Dance of the Song Dynasty |series=Musica Asiatica: volume 4| author= Laurence E. R. Picken |page=201 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year= 1984 |isbn=978-0-521-27837-9 }}</ref> Lions were first presented to the Han court by emissaries from Central Asia and [[Parthian Empire|Persia]], and were already popularly depicted as guardian figures by the sixth century AD.<ref name=japan>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=PcvA373XEJwC&pg=PA109#v=onepage |title=Asian Material Culture|editor= Marianne Hulsbosch |editor2=Elizabeth Bedford |editor3=Martha Chaiklin |page=109|publisher=Amsterdam University Press |year=2010 |isbn=9789089640901}}</ref> Today the guardian lions are more usually specified by reference to the medium or material, for example:\n* ''Stone lion'' ({{zh|c=\u77f3\u7345|p=Sh\u00edsh\u012b|labels=no}}): for a stone sculpture; or\n* ''Bronze lion'' ({{zh|c=\u9285\u7345|p=T\u00f3ngsh\u012b|labels=no}}): for a bronze sculpture.\n\nand less commonly:\n* ''Auspicious lion'' ({{zh|c=\u745e\u7345|p=Ru\u00ecsh\u012b|labels=no}}): referring to the Tibetan [[Snow Lion]] or good fortune\n\n=== In other Asian cultures ===\n[[File:Jiaoshi.JPG|thumb|Lioness and cubs from the [[Yuan Dynasty]] discovered inside [[Beijing city fortifications|Peking's city walls]]]]\n\n* In [[Japan]]: the lion figures are known as ''Shishi'' ({{lang|ja|\u7345\u5b50}}, lion) or ''[[Komainu]]'' ({{lang|ja|\u72db\u72ac}}, lion dogs)\n**In [[Okinawa]]: known as ''[[Shisa]]''\n* In [[Korea]]: known as ''[[Xiezhi|Haetae]]''\n* In [[Myanmar]] and [[Laos]]: known as ''[[Chinthe]]'' and gave their name to the [[World War II]] [[Chindit]] soldiers\n* In [[Cambodia]]: known as ''Singha'' or ''Sing'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17b9\u1784\u17d2\u17a0}})\n* In [[Sri Lanka]]: known as ''Simha'' ({{lang|ta|\u0dc3\u0dd2\u0d82\u0dc4 \u0db8\u0dd6\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dad\u0dd2}})\n* In [[Thailand]]: known as ''Singha'' ({{lang|th|\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e4c}})\n* In [[Tibet]]: known as a ''[[Snow Lion]]''\n* In [[Vietnam]]: known as ''{{lang|vi|S\u01b0 t\u1eed \u0111\u00e1}}''\n\n=== Western names ===\nIn English and several Western languages, the guardian lions are often referred in a multitude of name such as: \"Fu Dogs\",<ref>D. Eastlake, C. Manros, and E. Raymond, [http://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3092.txt RFC 3092: Etymology of \"Foo\"], The Internet Society, April 1, 2001.</ref> \"Foo Dogs\", \"Fu Lions\", \"Fo Lions\", and \"Lion Dogs\".<ref>Article ''[http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9048428/Lion-of-Fo Lion of Fo]'' at the Online version of ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''.</ref> The term \"''Fo''\" or \"''Fu''\" may be [[transliteration]]s to the words {{zh|c=\u4f5b|labels=no}} ({{zh|p=f\u00f3}}) or {{zh|c=\u798f|labels=no}} ({{zh|p=f\u00fa}}), which means \"Buddha\" or \"prosperity\" in Chinese, respectively. However, Chinese reference to the guardian lions are seldom prefixed with {{zh|c=\u4f5b|labels=no}} or {{zh|c=\u798f|labels=no}}, and more importantly never referred to as \"dogs\".{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nReference to guardian lions as dogs in Western cultures may be due to the Japanese reference to them as \"Korean dogs\" ({{lang|ja|\u72db\u72ac\u30fb\u9ad8\u9e97\u72ac}}) due to their transmission from China through Korea into Japan. It may also be due to the misidentification of the guardian lion figures as representing certain Chinese dog breeds such as the [[Chow Chow]] ({{zh|c=\u9b06\u7345\u72ac|labels=no|p=s\u014dngsh\u012b qu\u01cen|l=puffy-lion dog}}) or [[Pekingese]] ({{zh|c=\u7345\u5b50\u72d7|labels=no|p=Sh\u012bzi G\u01d2u|l=lion dog}}).\n\n== Appearance ==\n[[File:National Palace Museum RightSide Lion.JPG|thumb|right|Guardian lion at the [[National Palace Museum]] in [[Taipei]]]]\n\nThe lions are traditionally carved from decorative stone, such as marble and granite or cast in bronze or iron. Because of the high cost of these materials and the labor required to produce them, private use of guardian lions was traditionally reserved for wealthy or elite families. Indeed, a traditional symbol of a family's wealth or social status was the placement of guardian lions in front of the family home. However, in modern times less expensive lions, mass-produced in concrete and resin, have become available and their use is therefore no longer restricted to the elite.{{Citation needed|reason=No sources cited in entire paragraph|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe lions are always presented in pairs, a manifestation of [[yin and yang]], the female representing yin and the male yang.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} The male lion has its right front paw on a type of cloth ball{{Citation needed|reason=All stone lions have their paws on cloth balls? Or just some of them? Or this is common?|date=April 2018}} simply called an \"[[Temari (toy)|embroidered ball]]\" ({{zh|labels=no|p=xi\u00f9 qi\u00fa|c=\u7ee3\u7403}}), which is sometimes carved with a geometric pattern.{{Citation needed|reason=No sources cited for this aside|date=April 2018}} The female is essentially identical, but has a cub under the left paw, representing the cycle of life.{{Citation needed|reason=There is only one interpretation of this?|date=April 2018}} Symbolically, the female lion protects those dwelling inside (the living soul within){{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}, while the male guards the structure (the external material elements){{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. Sometimes the female has her mouth closed, and the male open{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. This symbolizes the enunciation of the sacred word \"om\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. However, Japanese adaptations state that the male is inhaling, representing life, while the female exhales, representing death{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. Other styles have both lions with a single large [[pearl]] in each of their partially opened mouths{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. The pearl is carved so that it can roll about in the lion's mouth but sized just large enough so that it can never be removed.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nAccording to [[feng shui]], correct placement of the lions is important to ensure their beneficial effect.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} When looking at the entrance from outside the building, facing the lions, the male lion with the ball is on the right, and the female with the cub is on the left.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nChinese lions are intended to reflect the emotion of the animal as opposed to the reality of the lion.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}  This is in distinct opposition to the traditional English lion which is a lifelike depiction of the animal.{{Citation needed|reason=What is an \"English\"lion? Do you mean Western? Also, Western lions are never stylized to show the emotion of the animal?|date=April 2018}}  The claws, teeth and eyes of the Chinese lion represent power.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}  Few if any muscles are visible in the Chinese lion {{Citation needed|reason=the Chinese lions look muscular.|date=April 2018}} whereas the English lion shows its power through its life-like characteristics rather than through stylized representation.{{Citation needed|reason=What is an \"English\"lion? Do you mean Western? Also, Western lions are never stylized to show the emotion of the animal?|date=April 2018}}\n\n== History ==\n[[Asiatic lion]]s are believed to be the ones depicted by the guardian lions in Chinese culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20021006/spectrum/art.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune \u2013 Spectrum \u2013 'Art and Soul|work=tribuneindia.com}}</ref>\n\nWith increased trade during the [[Han dynasty]] and cultural exchanges through the [[Silk road]], lions were introduced into China from the ancient states of Central Asia by peoples of [[Sogdiana]], [[Samarkand]], and the [[Yuezhi]] ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u6708\u6c0f}}) in the form of pelts and live tribute, along with stories about them from Buddhist priests and travelers of the time.<ref>Schafer, Edward H. (1963). ''The Golden Peaches of Samarkand, a Study of T'ang Exotics''. University of California Press.</ref>\n\nSeveral instances of lions as imperial tributes from Central Asia were recorded in the document ''[[Book of the Later Han]]'' ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u5f8c\u6f22\u66f8}}) written from 25-220 CE. On one particular event, on the eleventh lunar month of 87 CE, \"... an envoy from [[Parthia]] offered as tribute a lion and an ostrich\"<ref>{{cite book |quote={{lang|zh|\u5b89\u606f\u570b\u9063\u4f7f\u737b\u5e2b\u5b50\u53ca\u689d\u679d\u5927\u7235}}|script-title=zh:\u5f8c\u6f22\u66f8 |trans-title=[[Book of the Later Han]] |script-chapter=zh:\u5377\u56db\u5b5d\u548c\u5b5d\u6ba4\u5e1d\u7d00\u7b2c\u56db |trans-chapter=Annals of Emperor Xiaohe; Emperor Xiaoshang |url=https://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/%E5%BE%8C%E6%BC%A2%E6%9B%B8/%E5%8D%B74}}</ref> to the Han court. Indeed, the lion was associated by the Han Chinese to earlier venerated creatures of the ancient Chinese, most notably by the monk Huilin ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u6167\u7433}}) who stated that \"the mythic suan-ni ({{linktext|lang=zh|\u72fb\u730a}}) is actually the lion, coming from the [[Western Regions]]\" ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u72fb\u730a\u5373\u72ee\u5b50\u4e5f\uff0c\u51fa\u897f\u57df}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fantizi5.com/shenshou/longjiuzi/suanni/|script-title=zh:\u72fb\u730a\u4ecb\u7ecd(\u63d0\u95ee\uff1a\u72fb\u730a\u600e\u4e48\u8bfb\uff1f\u7b54\u6848\uff1a\u3010suanni\u3011) |trans-title=Suanni introduction (How to read {{lang|zh|\u72fb\u730a}}?) Answer: \"suanni\" |work=fantizi5.com}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Buddhist]] version of the Lion was originally introduced to Han China as the protector of [[dharma]] and these lions have been found in religious art as early as 208 BC. Gradually they were incorporated as guardians of the Chinese Imperial dharm. Lions seemed appropriately regal beasts to guard the emperor's gates and have been used as such since. There are various styles of guardian lions reflecting influences from different time periods, imperial dynasties, and regions of China. These styles vary in their artistic detail and adornment as well as in the depiction of the lions from fierce to serene.\n\nAlthough the form of the Chinese guardian lion was quite varied during its early history in China, the appearance, pose, and accessories of the lions eventually became standardized and formalized during the Ming and Qing dynasties into more or less its present form.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"170px\">\nFile:Suanni xianglu.JPG|A lion-like ''suanni'' depicted on the leg of an incense burner\nFile:Porcelaine chinoise Guimet 231104.jpg|A sitting lion statue, [[celadon]], 11th to 12th century, [[Song Dynasty]]\nFile:FuDog.JPG|A stone shi\nFile:ImperialMotherLionGuard.jpg|Female guardian lion with her cub at the [[Summer Palace]], [[Beijing]]- late [[Qing Dynasty]], but in the Ming style\nFile:ImperialLionCub.jpg|Cub Detail.\nFile:StandingMingLion.jpg|Standing lion at the [[Ming Dynasty Tombs]] [[Spirit Way]]\nFile:Imperial guardian lion - Ngee Ann City - Singapore (gabbe).jpg|Imperial guardian lion outside [[Ngee Ann City]] in [[Singapore]]\nFile:Guardian lion statue.jpg|Statue of a mystical Chinese guardian lion in old Beijing, China\nFile:China - Beijing 12 - lion outside the Tibetan Monastery (134036069).jpg|A guardian lion outside [[Yonghe Temple]], Beijing\nFile:Iron Lion of Cangzhou 2007.jpg|The [[Iron Lion of Cangzhou]], cast in 953 AD, is the largest known and oldest surviving iron-cast artwork in China\nFile:Chinese Guardian Lion 02.jpg|A guardian lion in [[Pingxi District]], Taiwan\nFile:Wen Wu Temple - Chinese lion.jpg|A guardian lion of Wen Wu Temple, Taiwan\nFile:Guardian Lions.jpg|A pair of guardian lions of Gaoyi [[Que (tower)|Que]], 209 AD Han Dynasty\nFile:\"Guardian Lion\" at Brooklyn Museum IMG 3865.JPG|Guardian Lion, [[Brooklyn Museum]], [[New York City]]\nFile:Chinese guardian lion at Petrovskaya Embankment.jpg|Guardian Lion in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]\n</gallery>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Literary references ==\n[[File:Female Chinese Lion Statue.jpg|thumb|100px|left|The left side statue represents [[Yin and yang|Yin]] force, [[female]], negative, take, carry a cub. <!-- [[Sanggar Agung]] Temple, [[Surabaya]], [[Indonesia]]. -->]]\n[[File:Male Chinese Lion Statue.jpg|thumb|100px|The right side statue represents [[Yin and yang|Yang]] force, [[male]], positive, bring, carry a ball. <!-- [[Sanggar Agung]] Temple, [[Surabaya]], [[Indonesia]]. -->]]\n\n* In the novelet \"White Magic\" by Albert E. Cowdrey (''Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction'', March 1998), the protagonist has a \"foo\" lion/dog that serves as his \"familiar\" and comes alive, when necessary, to protect him and his neighbors.\n* In the planned spinoffs of [[Gargoyles (comic)|the comics]] based on the [[Gargoyles (TV series)|''Gargoyles'']] Disney TV animated series, the [[Time travel|\"timedancing\"]] gargoyle [[Manhattan Clan#Clan members|Brooklyn]] receives a green-skinned, leonine gargoyle beast that is named \"fu-dog\" from the Western name of the guardian lion statuary.\n* Stone lions feature in a well-known Chinese tongue-twister: {{zh|labels=no|c=\u56db\u662f\u56db\uff0c\u5341\u662f\u5341\uff0c\u5341\u56db\u662f\u5341\u56db\uff0c\u56db\u5341\u662f\u56db\u5341\uff0c\u56db\u5341\u56db\u53ea\u77f3\u72ee\u5b50\u662f\u6b7b\u7684|p=s\u00ec sh\u00ec s\u00ec, sh\u00ed sh\u00ec sh\u00ed, sh\u00ed s\u00ec sh\u00ec sh\u00ed s\u00ec, s\u00ec sh\u00ed sh\u00ec s\u00ec sh\u00ed, s\u00ec sh\u00ed s\u00ec zh\u012b sh\u00ed sh\u012b z\u00ec sh\u00ec s\u01d0 de|l=4 is 4, 10 is 10, 14 is 14, 40 is 40, 44 stone lions are dead}}.\n* In ''The Dresden Files'' series by Jim Butcher, the protagonist Harry Dresden comes into possession of a \"Tibetan Temple Dog\", frequently also referred to as a Foo Dog or Foo Spirit.  Named \"Mouse\", he is depicted as an unusually large mastiff-like dog with human level intelligence, remarkable resilience and strength, as well as the ability to perceive and attack spirits and non-corporeal beings.\n* In Richard Russo's novel ''Nobody's Fool'', Miss Beryl Peoples owns a two-headed \"foo dog\" she purchased while travelling the Orient.  Miss Beryl claims it is called a \"foo\" dog because the dog says, \"Foo on you!\" when he is not approving of a person's actions.\n* In [[Roger Zelazny]]'s novel ''[[Lord Demon]]'', the protagonist Kai Wren has two Fu dogs as pets - the green male Shiriki and the orange-red female Shambhala.\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Komainu]] to compare its use in Japanese culture\n* [[Qilin]], another mythical creature in Chinese culture\n* [[Sphinx]]\n* [[Chinthe]] similar lion statues in Burma, Laos and Cambodia\n* [[Shisa]] similar lion statues in the Ryukyu Islands\n* [[Nian]] to compare with a similar but horned (unicorn) mythical beast\n* [[Pixiu]] to compare with a similar but winged mythical beast\n* [[Haetae]] to compare with similar lion-like statues in [[Korea]].  \n* [[Foo Dog (disambiguation)|Foo dog]], dog breeds originating in China that resemble \"Chinese guardian lions\" and hence are also called Lion Dogs.\n* [[Asiatic lion]]s found in nearby [[India]] are the ones depicted in the Chinese culture.\n* [[Piraeus Lion]]\n* Tibetan [[Snow Lion]]\n* [[Traditional Chinese Lions (Indianapolis Zoo)]]\n* [[Medici lions]]\n* [[Lion dance]], another use of lion imagery in costume and motion.\n* [[Culture of China]]\n* [[Chinese mythology]]\n* [[Chinese dragon]]\n* [[Door god]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Chinese lions}}\n* [http://thewildtattoo.com/foo-dog-tattoo-ideas/ Foo Dog in Tattoo Art. Meaning and Design Ideas].\n* [http://foodogblog.blogspot.com/ A blog about the adventures of a Foo Dog statue all over the United States].\n* [http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/90981/rec/1 ''Netsuke: masterpieces from the Metropolitan Museum of Art''], an exhibition catalog from The Metropolitan Museum of Art (fully available online as PDF), which contains many representations of Chinese guardian lions\n\n{{Chinese mythology}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese architectural history]]\n[[Category:Chinese legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Chinese mythology]]\n[[Category:Mythological dogs]]\n[[Category:Mythological canines]]\n[[Category:Mythological lions]]\n[[Category:Chinese culture]]\n[[Category:Buddhist legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of lions]]\n[[Category:Statues of lions with spheres]]\n[[Category:Dogs in religion]]\n[[Category:Lions in religion]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|Chinese architectural statues|dog breeds|Lion dog (disambiguation)|uses of colloquial term foo dogs|Foo Dog (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|title='''Chinese guardian lions'''\n|pic=ImperialMaleLionGuard.jpg\n|picsize=250px\n|piccap=A [[Ming Dynasty|Ming-era]] guardian lion in the [[Forbidden City]]\n|pic2=Forbidden City Imperial Guardian Lions.jpg\n|picsize2=250px|\npiccap2=A [[Qing Dynasty|Qing-era]] guardian lion pair in the Forbidden City. Note the different appearance of the face and details in the decorative items, compared to the earlier Ming version.\n|t={{linktext|\u7345}}([[:wikt:\u7345\u5b50|\u5b50]]) |s={{linktext|\u72ee}}([[:wikt:\u72ee\u5b50|\u5b50]]) |l=[[lion]] |p=sh\u012b(zi) |w=shi(-tzu) |y= |h= |poj=\n|t2                =  {{linktext|\u77f3\u7345}}([[:wikt:\u77f3\u7345\u5b50|\u5b50]])\n|s2                = {{linktext|\u77f3\u72ee}}([[:wikt:\u77f3\u72ee\u5b50|\u5b50]])\n|l2                =  [[stone]] [[lion]]\n|p2                =  sh\u00edsh\u012b(zi)\n|w2 = shih-shih(-tzu)\n|hangul            =  {{linktext|\ud574\ud0dc}}\n|hanja             =  {{linktext|\u6d77\u6cf0}}\n|rr                =  haetae\n|kanji             =  {{linktext|\u72db\u72ac}}\n|revhep            =  [[komainu]]\n|vie=s\u01b0 t\u1eed \u0111\u00e1\n|chuhan = {{linktext|\u7345\u5b50|\ud855\udca5}}\n|lang1=Khmer\n|lang1_content= \u179f\u17b9\u1784\u17d2\u17a0<br/> singha\n|lang2=Thai\n|lang2_content= \u0e2a\u0e34\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e4c<br/> s\u0304ingh\u0304\u0312\n|lang3=Sinhalese\n|lang3_content= \u0dc3\u0dd2\u0d82\u0dc4<br/> si\u1e41ha\n|lang4=Burmese\n|lang4_content= \u1001\u103c\u1004\u103a\u1039\u101e\u1031\u1037<br/> hkyin-sae\n|lang5=Tibetan\n|lang5_content= \u0f42\u0f44\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f7a\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f7a\u0f0b<br/> gangs-seng-ge\n}}\n{{Contains Indic text}} \n'''Chinese''' or '''Imperial guardian lions''' are a traditional [[Chinese architecture|Chinese architectural]] ornament. Typically made of [[stone]], they are also known as '''stone{{nbsp}}lions''' or '''shishi'''. They are known in colloquial English as '''lion{{nbsp}}dogs''' or '''foo{{nbsp}}dogs'''. The concept, which originated and became popular in [[Chinese Buddhism]], features a pair of highly stylized [[lion]]s\u2014often one male with a ball and one female with a [[lion cub|cub]]\u2014which were thought to protect the building from harmful spiritual influences and harmful people that might be a threat. Used in [[imperial China|imperial Chinese]] palaces and [[Chinese tomb|tombs]], the lions subsequently spread to other parts of Asia including Japan (see [[komainu]]), Korea, Tibet, Thailand, Burma, Vietnam, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Cambodia, Laos, Taiwan, and Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|author=K Gorman |url=http://kgorman.ca/monster-monday-guardian-lions/ |title=Monster Monday: Guardian Lions \u2013 K. Gorman |publisher=Kgorman.ca |date= 22 January 2013|accessdate=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nStatues of guardian lions have traditionally stood in front of [[China|Chinese]] Imperial palaces, Imperial tombs, government offices, temples, and the homes of government officials and the wealthy, and were believed to have powerful [[Chinese mythology|mythic]] protective benefits. They are also used in other artistic contexts, for example on door-knockers, and in pottery. Pairs of guardian lion statues are still common decorative and symbolic elements at the entrances to restaurants, hotels, supermarkets and other structures, with one sitting on each side of the entrance, in China and in other places around the world where the Chinese people have immigrated and settled, especially in local [[Chinatown]]s.\n\nThe lions are usually depicted in pairs. When used as statuary the pair would consist of a male leaning his paw upon an embroidered ball (in imperial contexts, representing supremacy over the world) and a female restraining a playful cub that is on its back (representing nurture).<ref name=\"britannica.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/342714/Lion-of-Fo|title=Lion of Fo \u2013 Chinese art|encyclopedia=britannica.com}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nGuardian lions are referred to in various ways depending on language and context. In Chinese they are traditionally called simply ''shi'' ({{zh|c=\u7345|p=sh\u012b}}) meaning lion\u2014the word ''shi'' itself is thought to be derived from the Persian word ''\u0161er''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Xy45AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA201#v=onepage |title=Music for a Lion Dance of the Song Dynasty |series=Musica Asiatica: volume 4| author= Laurence E. R. Picken |page=201 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year= 1984 |isbn=978-0-521-27837-9 }}</ref> Lions were first presented to the Han court by emissaries from Central Asia and [[Parthian Empire|Persia]], and were already popularly depicted as guardian figures by the sixth century AD.<ref name=japan>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=PcvA373XEJwC&pg=PA109#v=onepage |title=Asian Material Culture|editors= Marianne Hulsbosch, Elizabeth Bedford, Martha Chaiklin |page=109|publisher=Amsterdam University Press |year=2010 |isbn=9789089640901}}</ref> Today the guardian lions are more usually specified by reference to the medium or material, for example:\n* ''Stone lion'' ({{zh|c=\u77f3\u7345|p=Sh\u00edsh\u012b|labels=no}}): for a stone sculpture; or\n* ''Bronze lion'' ({{zh|c=\u9285\u7345|p=T\u00f3ngsh\u012b|labels=no}}): for a bronze sculpture.\n\nand less commonly:\n* ''Auspicious lion'' ({{zh|c=\u745e\u7345|p=Ru\u00ecsh\u012b|labels=no}}): referring to the Tibetan [[Snow Lion]] or good fortune\n\n=== In other Asian cultures ===\n[[File:Jiaoshi.JPG|thumb|Lioness and cubs from the [[Yuan Dynasty]] discovered inside [[Beijing city fortifications|Peking's city walls]]]]\n\n* In [[Japan]]: the lion figures are known as ''Shishi'' ({{lang|ja|\u7345\u5b50}}, lion) or ''[[Komainu]]'' ({{lang|ja|\u72db\u72ac}}, lion dogs)\n**In [[Okinawa]]: known as ''[[Shisa]]''\n* In [[Korea]]: known as ''[[Xiezhi|Haetae]]''\n* In [[Myanmar]] and [[Laos]]: known as ''[[Chinthe]]'' and gave their name to the [[World War II]] [[Chindit]] soldiers\n* In [[Cambodia]]: known as ''Singha'' or ''Sing'' ({{lang|km|\u179f\u17b9\u1784\u17d2\u17a0}})\n* In [[Sri Lanka]]: known as ''Simha'' ({{lang|ta|\u0dc3\u0dd2\u0d82\u0dc4 \u0db8\u0dd6\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dad\u0dd2}})\n* In [[Thailand]]: known as ''Singha'' ({{lang|th|\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e4c}})\n* In [[Tibet]]: known as a ''[[Snow Lion]]''\n* In [[Vietnam]]: known as ''{{lang|vi|S\u01b0 t\u1eed \u0111\u00e1}}''\n\n=== Western names ===\nIn English and several Western languages, the guardian lions are often referred in a multitude of name such as: \"Fu Dogs\",<ref>D. Eastlake, C. Manros, and E. Raymond, [http://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3092.txt RFC 3092: Etymology of \"Foo\"], The Internet Society, April 1, 2001.</ref> \"Foo Dogs\", \"Fu Lions\", \"Fo Lions\", and \"Lion Dogs\".<ref>Article ''[http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9048428/Lion-of-Fo Lion of Fo]'' at the Online version of ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''.</ref> The term \"''Fo''\" or \"''Fu''\" may be [[transliteration]]s to the words {{zh|c=\u4f5b|labels=no}} ({{zh|p=f\u00f3}}) or {{zh|c=\u798f|labels=no}} ({{zh|p=f\u00fa}}), which means \"Buddha\" or \"prosperity\" in Chinese, respectively. However, Chinese reference to the guardian lions are seldom prefixed with {{zh|c=\u4f5b|labels=no}} or {{zh|c=\u798f|labels=no}}, and more importantly never referred to as \"dogs\".{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nReference to guardian lions as dogs in Western cultures may be due to the Japanese reference to them as \"Korean dogs\" ({{lang|ja|\u72db\u72ac\u30fb\u9ad8\u9e97\u72ac}}) due to their transmission from China through Korea into Japan. It may also be due to the misidentification of the guardian lion figures as representing certain Chinese dog breeds such as the [[Chow Chow]] ({{zh|c=\u9b06\u7345\u72ac|labels=no|p=s\u014dngsh\u012b qu\u01cen|l=puffy-lion dog}}) or [[Pekingese]] ({{zh|c=\u7345\u5b50\u72d7|labels=no|p=Sh\u012bzi G\u01d2u|l=lion dog}}).\n\n== Appearance ==\n[[File:National Palace Museum RightSide Lion.JPG|thumb|right|Guardian lion at the [[National Palace Museum]] in [[Taipei]]]]\n\nThe lions are traditionally carved from decorative stone, such as marble and granite or cast in bronze or iron. Because of the high cost of these materials and the labor required to produce them, private use of guardian lions was traditionally reserved for wealthy or elite families. Indeed, a traditional symbol of a family's wealth or social status was the placement of guardian lions in front of the family home. However, in modern times less expensive lions, mass-produced in concrete and resin, have become available and their use is therefore no longer restricted to the elite.{{Citation needed|reason=No sources cited in entire paragraph|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe lions are always presented in pairs, a manifestation of [[yin and yang]], the female representing yin and the male yang.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} The male lion has its right front paw on a type of cloth ball{{Citation needed|reason=All stone lions have their paws on cloth balls? Or just some of them? Or this is common?|date=April 2018}} simply called an \"[[Temari (toy)|embroidered ball]]\" ({{zh|labels=no|p=xi\u00f9 qi\u00fa|c=\u7ee3\u7403}}), which is sometimes carved with a geometric pattern.{{Citation needed|reason=No sources cited for this aside|date=April 2018}} The female is essentially identical, but has a cub under the left paw, representing the cycle of life.{{Citation needed|reason=There is only one interpretation of this?|date=April 2018}} Symbolically, the female lion protects those dwelling inside (the living soul within){{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}, while the male guards the structure (the external material elements){{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. Sometimes the female has her mouth closed, and the male open{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. This symbolizes the enunciation of the sacred word \"om\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. However, Japanese adaptations state that the male is inhaling, representing life, while the female exhales, representing death{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. Other styles have both lions with a single large [[pearl]] in each of their partially opened mouths{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}. The pearl is carved so that it can roll about in the lion's mouth but sized just large enough so that it can never be removed.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nAccording to [[feng shui]], correct placement of the lions is important to ensure their beneficial effect.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} When looking at the entrance from outside the building, facing the lions, the male lion with the ball is on the right, and the female with the cub is on the left.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nChinese lions are intended to reflect the emotion of the animal as opposed to the reality of the lion.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}  This is in distinct opposition to the traditional English lion which is a lifelike depiction of the animal.{{Citation needed|reason=What is an \"English\"lion? Do you mean Western? Also, Western lions are never stylized to show the emotion of the animal?|date=April 2018}}  The claws, teeth and eyes of the Chinese lion represent power.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}  Few if any muscles are visible in the Chinese lion {{Citation needed|reason=the Chinese lions look muscular.|date=April 2018}} whereas the English lion shows its power through its life-like characteristics rather than through stylized representation.{{Citation needed|reason=What is an \"English\"lion? Do you mean Western? Also, Western lions are never stylized to show the emotion of the animal?|date=April 2018}}\n\n== History ==\n[[Asiatic lion]]s are believed to be the ones depicted by the guardian lions in Chinese culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20021006/spectrum/art.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune \u2013 Spectrum \u2013 'Art and Soul|work=tribuneindia.com}}</ref>\n\nWith increased trade during the [[Han dynasty]] and cultural exchanges through the [[Silk road]], lions were introduced into China from the ancient states of Central Asia by peoples of [[Sogdiana]], [[Samarkand]], and the [[Yuezhi]] ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u6708\u6c0f}}) in the form of pelts and live tribute, along with stories about them from Buddhist priests and travelers of the time.<ref>Schafer, Edward H. (1963). ''The Golden Peaches of Samarkand, a Study of T'ang Exotics''. University of California Press.</ref>\n\nSeveral instances of lions as imperial tributes from Central Asia were recorded in the document ''[[Book of the Later Han]]'' ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u5f8c\u6f22\u66f8}}) written from 25-220 CE. On one particular event, on the eleventh lunar month of 87 CE, \"... an envoy from [[Parthia]] offered as tribute a lion and an ostrich\"<ref>{{cite book |quote={{lang|zh|\u5b89\u606f\u570b\u9063\u4f7f\u737b\u5e2b\u5b50\u53ca\u689d\u679d\u5927\u7235}}|script-title=zh:\u5f8c\u6f22\u66f8 |trans-title=[[Book of the Later Han]] |script-chapter=zh:\u5377\u56db\u5b5d\u548c\u5b5d\u6ba4\u5e1d\u7d00\u7b2c\u56db |trans-chapter=Annals of Emperor Xiaohe; Emperor Xiaoshang |url=https://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/%E5%BE%8C%E6%BC%A2%E6%9B%B8/%E5%8D%B74}}</ref> to the Han court. Indeed, the lion was associated by the Han Chinese to earlier venerated creatures of the ancient Chinese, most notably by the monk Huilin ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u6167\u7433}}) who stated that \"the mythic suan-ni ({{linktext|lang=zh|\u72fb\u730a}}) is actually the lion, coming from the [[Western Regions]]\" ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u72fb\u730a\u5373\u72ee\u5b50\u4e5f\uff0c\u51fa\u897f\u57df}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fantizi5.com/shenshou/longjiuzi/suanni/|script-title=zh:\u72fb\u730a\u4ecb\u7ecd(\u63d0\u95ee\uff1a\u72fb\u730a\u600e\u4e48\u8bfb\uff1f\u7b54\u6848\uff1a\u3010suanni\u3011) |trans-title=Suanni introduction (How to read {{lang|zh|\u72fb\u730a}}?) Answer: \"suanni\" |work=fantizi5.com}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Buddhist]] version of the Lion was originally introduced to Han China as the protector of [[dharma]] and these lions have been found in religious art as early as 208 BC. Gradually they were incorporated as guardians of the Chinese Imperial dharm. Lions seemed appropriately regal beasts to guard the emperor's gates and have been used as such since. There are various styles of guardian lions reflecting influences from different time periods, imperial dynasties, and regions of China. These styles vary in their artistic detail and adornment as well as in the depiction of the lions from fierce to serene.\n\nAlthough the form of the Chinese guardian lion was quite varied during its early history in China, the appearance, pose, and accessories of the lions eventually became standardized and formalized during the Ming and Qing dynasties into more or less its present form.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"170px\">\nFile:Suanni xianglu.JPG|A lion-like ''suanni'' depicted on the leg of an incense burner\nFile:Porcelaine chinoise Guimet 231104.jpg|A sitting lion statue, [[celadon]], 11th to 12th century, [[Song Dynasty]]\nFile:FuDog.JPG|A stone shi\nFile:ImperialMotherLionGuard.jpg|Female guardian lion with her cub at the [[Summer Palace]], [[Beijing]]- late [[Qing Dynasty]], but in the Ming style\nFile:ImperialLionCub.jpg|Cub Detail.\nFile:StandingMingLion.jpg|Standing lion at the [[Ming Dynasty Tombs]] [[Spirit Way]]\nFile:Imperial guardian lion - Ngee Ann City - Singapore (gabbe).jpg|Imperial guardian lion outside [[Ngee Ann City]] in [[Singapore]]\nFile:Guardian lion statue.jpg|Statue of a mystical Chinese guardian lion in old Beijing, China\nFile:China - Beijing 12 - lion outside the Tibetan Monastery (134036069).jpg|A guardian lion outside [[Yonghe Temple]], Beijing\nFile:Iron Lion of Cangzhou 2007.jpg|The [[Iron Lion of Cangzhou]], cast in 953 AD, is the largest known and oldest surviving iron-cast artwork in China\nFile:Chinese Guardian Lion 02.jpg|A guardian lion in [[Pingxi District]], Taiwan\nFile:Wen Wu Temple - Chinese lion.jpg|A guardian lion of Wen Wu Temple, Taiwan\nFile:Guardian Lions.jpg|A pair of guardian lions of Gaoyi [[Que (tower)|Que]], 209 AD Han Dynasty\nFile:\"Guardian Lion\" at Brooklyn Museum IMG 3865.JPG|Guardian Lion, [[Brooklyn Museum]], [[New York City]]\nFile:Chinese guardian lion at Petrovskaya Embankment.jpg|Guardian Lion in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]\n</gallery>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Literary references ==\n[[File:Female Chinese Lion Statue.jpg|thumb|100px|left|The left side statue represents [[Yin and yang|Yin]] force, [[female]], negative, take, carry a cub. <!-- [[Sanggar Agung]] Temple, [[Surabaya]], [[Indonesia]]. -->]]\n[[File:Male Chinese Lion Statue.jpg|thumb|100px|The right side statue represents [[Yin and yang|Yang]] force, [[male]], positive, bring, carry a ball. <!-- [[Sanggar Agung]] Temple, [[Surabaya]], [[Indonesia]]. -->]]\n\n* In the novelet \"White Magic\" by Albert E. Cowdrey (''Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction'', March 1998), the protagonist has a \"foo\" lion/dog that serves as his \"familiar\" and comes alive, when necessary, to protect him and his neighbors.\n* In the planned spinoffs of [[Gargoyles (comic)|the comics]] based on the [[Gargoyles (TV series)|''Gargoyles'']] Disney TV animated series, the [[Time travel|\"timedancing\"]] gargoyle [[Manhattan Clan#Clan members|Brooklyn]] receives a green-skinned, leonine gargoyle beast that is named \"fu-dog\" from the Western name of the guardian lion statuary.\n* Stone lions feature in a well-known Chinese tongue-twister: {{zh|labels=no|c=\u56db\u662f\u56db\uff0c\u5341\u662f\u5341\uff0c\u5341\u56db\u662f\u5341\u56db\uff0c\u56db\u5341\u662f\u56db\u5341\uff0c\u56db\u5341\u56db\u53ea\u77f3\u72ee\u5b50\u662f\u6b7b\u7684|p=s\u00ec sh\u00ec s\u00ec, sh\u00ed sh\u00ec sh\u00ed, sh\u00ed s\u00ec sh\u00ec sh\u00ed s\u00ec, s\u00ec sh\u00ed sh\u00ec s\u00ec sh\u00ed, s\u00ec sh\u00ed s\u00ec zh\u012b sh\u00ed sh\u012b z\u00ec sh\u00ec s\u01d0 de|l=4 is 4, 10 is 10, 14 is 14, 40 is 40, 44 stone lions are dead}}.\n* In ''The Dresden Files'' series by Jim Butcher, the protagonist Harry Dresden comes into possession of a \"Tibetan Temple Dog\", frequently also referred to as a Foo Dog or Foo Spirit.  Named \"Mouse\", he is depicted as an unusually large mastiff-like dog with human level intelligence, remarkable resilience and strength, as well as the ability to perceive and attack spirits and non-corporeal beings.\n* In Richard Russo's novel ''Nobody's Fool'', Miss Beryl Peoples owns a two-headed \"foo dog\" she purchased while travelling the Orient.  Miss Beryl claims it is called a \"foo\" dog because the dog says, \"Foo on you!\" when he is not approving of a person's actions.\n* In [[Roger_Zelazny|Roger Zelazny]]'s novel [[Lord_Demon|''Lord Demon'']], the protagonist Kai Wren has two Fu dogs as pets - the green male Shiriki and the orange-red female Shambhala.\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Komainu]] to compare its use in Japanese culture\n* [[Qilin]], another mythical creature in Chinese culture\n* [[Sphinx]]\n* [[Chinthe]] similar lion statues in Burma, Laos and Cambodia\n* [[Shisa]] similar lion statues in the Ryukyu Islands\n* [[Nian]] to compare with a similar but horned (unicorn) mythical beast\n* [[Pixiu]] to compare with a similar but winged mythical beast\n* [[Haetae]] to compare with similar lion-like statues in [[Korea]].  \n* [[Foo Dog (disambiguation)|Foo dog]], dog breeds originating in China that resemble \"Chinese guardian lions\" and hence are also called Lion Dogs.\n* [[Asiatic lion]]s found in nearby [[India]] are the ones depicted in the Chinese culture.\n* [[Piraeus Lion]]\n* Tibetan [[Snow Lion]]\n* [[Traditional Chinese Lions (Indianapolis Zoo)]]\n* [[Medici lions]]\n* [[Lion dance]], another use of lion imagery in costume and motion.\n* [[Culture of China]]\n* [[Chinese mythology]]\n* [[Chinese dragon]]\n* [[Door god]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Chinese lions}}\n* [http://thewildtattoo.com/foo-dog-tattoo-ideas/ Foo Dog in Tattoo Art. Meaning and Design Ideas].\n* [http://foodogblog.blogspot.com/ A blog about the adventures of a Foo Dog statue all over the United States].\n* [http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/90981/rec/1 ''Netsuke: masterpieces from the Metropolitan Museum of Art''], an exhibition catalog from The Metropolitan Museum of Art (fully available online as PDF), which contains many representations of Chinese guardian lions\n\n{{Chinese mythology}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese architectural history]]\n[[Category:Chinese legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Chinese mythology]]\n[[Category:Mythological dogs]]\n[[Category:Mythological canines]]\n[[Category:Mythological lions]]\n[[Category:Chinese culture]]\n[[Category:Buddhist legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of lions]]\n[[Category:Statues of lions with spheres]]\n[[Category:Dogs in religion]]\n[[Category:Lions in religion]]\n", "name_user": "IznoRepeat", "label": "safe", "comment": "replace soft-deprecated editors parameter, gen fixes, misc cite cleaning", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_guardian_lions"}
{"title_page": "Caribbean Public Health Agency", "text_new": "{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name     = Caribbean Public Health Agency\n|logo            = \n|logo_width      = \n|logo_caption    =\n|seal            =\n|seal_width      =\n|seal_caption    =\n|formed          = {{Start date and age|2013}}<ref name=\"caribjournal-2011\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.caribjournal.com/2011/06/15/caricom-to-establish-regional-health-agency/ |title=CARICOM to Establish Health Agency |date=15 June 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Caribbean Journal}}</ref>\n|preceding1      = The Caribbean Environmental Health Institute (CEHI)\n|preceding2      = The Caribbean Epidemiology Centre (CAREC)\n|preceding3      = The Caribbean Food and Nutrition Institute (CFNI)\n|preceding4      = The Caribbean Health Research Council (CHRC)\n|preceding5      = The Caribbean Regional Drug Testing Laboratory (CRDTL)\n|dissolved       =\n|superseding     =\n|jurisdiction    = [[Caribbean_Community|CARICOM]]\n|headquarters    = {{nowrap|{{flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}} [[Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago]]}}\n|coordinates     = {{Coord|10|40|26|N|61|31|28|W|display=inline,title}}\n|employees       = \n|budget          = \n|minister1_name  =\n|minister1_pfo   =\n|minister2_name  =\n|minister2_pfo   =\n|chief1_name     = Dr. Cheryl Joy St. John\n|chief1_position = Executive Director\n|parent_agency   = \n|website         = http://www.carpha.org/\n}}\n\nThe '''Caribbean Public Health Agency''' (CARPHA) is a regional public health agency headquartered in [[Trinidad and Tobago]]<ref name=\"caricom-2013\">{{Cite web |url=https://caricom.org/remarks-by-ambassador-irwin-larocque-secretary-general-of-the-caribbean-community-caricom-at-the-launch-of-the-caribbean-public-health-agency-carpha/ |title=Remarks by Ambassador Irwin LaRocque, Secretary-General of the Caribbean Community, (CARICOM) At The Launch of the Caribbean Public Health Agency (CARPHA) |date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=CARICOM}}</ref> which was established by [[Caribbean_Community|CARICOM]] leaders in July 2011<ref name=\"caribjournal-2011\" /> and began operation in 2013<ref name=\"caricom-2013\" />.\n\nCARPHA combines the functions of five pre-existing regional health institutions:<ref name=\"kaieteurnew-2012\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.kaieteurnewsonline.com/2012/12/18/caribbean-public-health-agency-to-launch-operations-in-2013/ |title=Caribbean Public Health Agency to launch operations in 2013 |date=18 December 2012 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Kaieteur News}}</ref>\n* The Caribbean Environmental Health Institute (CEHI)\n* The Caribbean Epidemiology Centre (CAREC)\n* The Caribbean Food and Nutrition Institute (CFNI)\n* The Caribbean Health Research Centre (CHRC)\n* The Caribbean Research and Drug Treatment Laboratory (CRDTL)\n\n\n==Role==\n\nCARPHA's self-stated mission is \"As a professional organisation to build member states' capacity to prevent [[disease]] and promote [[health|health and wellness]] through leadership, partnership and innovation in [[public health]]\".<ref name=\"carpha-about-2020\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.carpha.org/About |title=About The Caribbean Public Health Agency (CARPHA) |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=CARPHA}}</ref>\n\nCARPHA aims to address regional issues including:<ref name=\"carpha-about-2020\" />\n* Responding to disasters like [[Tropical_cyclone|hurricanes]], [[Earthquake|earthquakes]], and [[Flood|flooding]].\n* Monitoring and managing both [[Infection|communicable diseases]] (eg [[HIV/AIDS]] and [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|COVID-19]]) and [[Non-communicable_disease|non communicable diseases]] (eg [[obesity]] and [[diabetes]]) that are prevalent in the region.\n* Monitoring and preventing injuries, violence and illnesses in work places.\n* Contributing to global health agreements and compliance with international health regulations.\n\n===COVID-19===\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] CARPHA has been performing tests for 18 countries in the region but warned on 5 April 2020 that they were running short on reagents required for [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|COVID-19]] testing and at current levels expected to be able to continue testing for three weeks.<ref name=\"jamaicaobserver-5april\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/global-shortage-of-key-ingredient-could-affect-covid-19-testing-in-caribbean_191350 |title=Global shortage of key ingredient could affect COVID-19 testing in Caribbean |date=5 April 2020 |website=Jamaica Observer}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2020, the [[European Union]] announced a grant of \u20ac8M (US$8.6M), which will be implemented by the Caribbean Public Health Agency, for the fight against the Corona virus. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kaieteurnewsonline.com/2020/04/09/eu-provides-us8-6m-grant-for-cbean-to-combat-covid-19/|title=\nEU provides US$8.6M grant for C\u2019bean to combat COVID-19|website=Kaieteur News|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Membership ==\n\nCurrently CARPHA has 24 full members throughout the Americas.<ref name=\"carpha-members-2020\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.carpha.org/Who-We-Are/Member-States |title=Member States |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=CARPHA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country !! Joined  !! Population\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Anguilla}}[[Anguilla]]||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Antigua and Barbuda}}[[Antigua and Barbuda]] ||- || - \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Aruba}}[[Aruba]]||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Bahamas}}[[Bahamas]]||- || - \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Barbados}}[[Barbados]]||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Belize}}[[Belize]] ||- || - \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Bermuda}}[[Bermuda]] ||- || - \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Caribbean Netherlands}}[[BES Islands]] ([[Bonaire]], [[Sint Eustatius]], [[Saba]])||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|British Virgin Islands}}[[British Virgin Islands]]||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Cayman Islands}}[[Cayman Islands]]||- ||-\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Curacao}}[[Curacao]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Dominica}}[[Dominica]]  ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Grenada}}[[Grenada]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Haiti}}[[Haiti]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Guyana}}[[Guyana]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Jamaica}}[[Jamaica]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Montserrat}}[[Montserrat]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}[[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Saint Lucia}}[[Saint Lucia]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|St. Maarten}}[[St. Maarten]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}[[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Suriname}}[[Suriname]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}}[[Trinidad and Tobago]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Turks and Caicos Islands}}[[Turks and Caicos Islands]] ||- || -\n|}\n\n==See also==\nFor similar agencies, please see the [[List of national public health agencies]]\n* [[Pan American Health Organization|PAHO]]\n* [[World Health Organization]] (WHO; {{flag|United Nations}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.carpha.org/}}\n\n[[Category:Public health organizations]]\n[[Category:Institutions of the Caribbean Community]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in Trinidad and Tobago]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Caribbean|Medicine}}\n{{Americas topic|Health in}}\n{{Bioterrorism}}\n{{Public health}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name     = Caribbean Public Health Agency\n|logo            = \n|logo_width      = \n|logo_caption    =\n|seal            =\n|seal_width      =\n|seal_caption    =\n|formed          = {{Start date and age|2013}}<ref name=\"caribjournal-2011\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.caribjournal.com/2011/06/15/caricom-to-establish-regional-health-agency/ |title=CARICOM to Establish Health Agency |date=15 June 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Caribbean Journal}}</ref>\n|preceding1      = The Caribbean Environmental Health Institute (CEHI)\n|preceding2      = The Caribbean Epidemiology Centre (CAREC)\n|preceding3      = The Caribbean Food and Nutrition Institute (CFNI)\n|preceding4      = The Caribbean Health Research Council (CHRC)\n|preceding5      = The Caribbean Regional Drug Testing Laboratory (CRDTL)\n|dissolved       =\n|superseding     =\n|jurisdiction    = [[Caribbean_Community|CARICOM]]\n|headquarters    = {{nowrap|{{flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}} [[Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago]]}}\n|coordinates     = {{Coord|10|40|26|N|61|31|28|W|display=inline,title}}\n|employees       = \n|budget          = \n|minister1_name  =\n|minister1_pfo   =\n|minister2_name  =\n|minister2_pfo   =\n|chief1_name     = Dr. Cheryl Joy St. John\n|chief1_position = Executive Director\n|parent_agency   = \n|website         = http://www.carpha.org/\n}}\n\nThe '''Caribbean Public Health Agency''' (CARPHA) is a regional public health agency headquartered in [[Trinidad and Tobago]]<ref name=\"caricom-2013\">{{Cite web |url=https://caricom.org/remarks-by-ambassador-irwin-larocque-secretary-general-of-the-caribbean-community-caricom-at-the-launch-of-the-caribbean-public-health-agency-carpha/ |title=Remarks by Ambassador Irwin LaRocque, Secretary-General of the Caribbean Community, (CARICOM) At The Launch of the Caribbean Public Health Agency (CARPHA) |date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=CARICOM}}</ref> which was established by [[Caribbean_Community|CARICOM]] leaders in July 2011<ref name=\"caribjournal-2011\" /> and began operation in 2013<ref name=\"caricom-2013\" />.\n\nCARPHA combines the functions of five pre-existing regional health institutions:<ref name=\"kaieteurnew-2012\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.kaieteurnewsonline.com/2012/12/18/caribbean-public-health-agency-to-launch-operations-in-2013/ |title=Caribbean Public Health Agency to launch operations in 2013 |date=18 December 2012 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Kaieteur News}}</ref>\n* The Caribbean Environmental Health Institute (CEHI)\n* The Caribbean Epidemiology Centre (CAREC)\n* The Caribbean Food and Nutrition Institute (CFNI)\n* The Caribbean Health Research Centre (CHRC)\n* The Caribbean Research and Drug Treatment Laboratory (CRDTL)\n\n\n==Role==\n\nCARPHA's self-stated mission is \"As a professional organisation to build member states' capacity to prevent [[disease]] and promote [[health|health and wellness]] through leadership, partnership and innovation in [[public health]]\".<ref name=\"carpha-about-2020\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.carpha.org/About |title=About The Caribbean Public Health Agency (CARPHA) |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=CARPHA}}</ref>\n\nCARPHA aims to address regional issues including:<ref name=\"carpha-about-2020\" />\n* Responding to disasters like [[Tropical_cyclone|hurricanes]], [[Earthquake|earthquakes]], and [[Flood|flooding]].\n* Monitoring and managing both [[Infection|communicable diseases]] (eg [[HIV/AIDS]] and [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|COVID-19]]) and [[Non-communicable_disease|non communicable diseases]] (eg [[obesity]] and [[diabetes]]) that are prevalent in the region.\n* Monitoring and preventing injuries, violence and illnesses in work places.\n* Contributing to global health agreements and compliance with international health regulations.\n\n===COVID-19===\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] CARPHA has been performing tests for 18 countries in the region but warned on 5 April 2020 that they were running short on reagents required for [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|COVID-19]] testing and at current levels expected to be able to continue testing for three weeks.<ref name=\"jamaicaobserver-5april\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/global-shortage-of-key-ingredient-could-affect-covid-19-testing-in-caribbean_191350 |title=Global shortage of key ingredient could affect COVID-19 testing in Caribbean |date=5 April 2020 |website=Jamaica Observer}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2020, the [[European Union]] announced a grant of \u20ac8M (US$8.6M), which will be implemented by the Caribbean Public Health Agency, for the fight against the Corona virus. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kaieteurnewsonline.com/2020/04/09/eu-provides-us8-6m-grant-for-cbean-to-combat-covid-19/|title=\nEU provides US$8.6M grant for C\u2019bean to combat COVID-19|website=Kaieteur News|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Membership ==\n\nCurrently CARPHA has 24 full members throughout the Americas.<ref name=\"carpha-members-2020\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.carpha.org/Who-We-Are/Member-States |title=Member States |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=CARPHA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country !! Joined  !! Population\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Anguilla}}[[Anguilla]]||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Antigua and Barbuda}}[[Antigua and Barbuda]] ||- || - \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Aruba}}[[Aruba]]||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Bahamas}}[[Bahamas]]||- || - \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Barbados}}[[Barbados]]||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Belize}}[[Belize]] ||- || - \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Bermuda}}[[Bermuda]] ||- || - \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Caribbean Netherlands}}[[BES Islands]] ([[Bonaire]], [[Sint Eustatius]], [[Saba]])||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|British Virgin Islands}}[[British Virgin Islands]]||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Cayman Islands}}[[Cayman Islands]]||- ||-\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Curacao}}[[Curacao]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Dominica}}[[Dominica]]  ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Grenada}}[[Grenada]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Haiti}}[[Haiti]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Guyana}}[[Guyana]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Jamaica}}[[Jamaica]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Montserrat}}[[Montserrat]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}[[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Saint Lucia}}[[Saint Lucia]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|St. Maarten}}[[St. Maarten]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}[[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Suriname}}[[Suriname]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}}[[Trinidad and Tobago]] ||- || -\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Turks and Caicos Islands}}[[Turks and Caicos Islands]] |